{"key":"post-20002235","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>20002235</id>\n<content>Casing mixes should be non-nutritious or they're considered additional layers of substrate, not casing.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You don't want a casing layer to fully colonize.&amp;nbsp; The uncolonized parts hold water until the colonized parts can absorb it into the mycelium.&amp;nbsp; If you use substrate material as a casing, it fully colonizes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;One drawback which may have happened above is the time between spawning the bulk substrate and applying the casing layer allows a lot of time for contaminant spores to land on the surface.&amp;nbsp; They're then protected while they germinate and begin to grow under the casing.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>20002321</next>\n<prev>20002162</prev>\n<first>19979607</first>\n<last>20946217</last>\n<when>1400361430</when>\n<utime>05/18/14 12:17 AM</utime>\n</post>"}